got the gig because I did a game called Destroy All Humans.

15
00:02:22,867 --> 00:02:25,171
And the audio director, Emily Ridgway,

16
00:02:25,231 --> 00:02:26,794
went to work in Rational Games and said,

17
00:02:26,814 --> 00:02:27,996
you've got to hire Gary Scheinman.

18
00:02:28,677 --> 00:02:29,398
And so they did.

19
00:02:29,539 --> 00:02:31,502
And so it's been a very important.

20
00:02:33,107 --> 00:02:36,189
part of my career, these three really, really beautiful games.

21
00:02:37,350 --> 00:02:40,373
But Infinite really was...

22
00:02:40,393 --> 00:02:44,436
Bioshock 1 had its own unique style,

23
00:02:44,777 --> 00:02:47,980
and Bioshock 2 also utilized the style of Bioshock 1.

24
00:02:48,040 --> 00:02:48,940
It was really, it was a true...

25
00:02:50,922 --> 00:02:54,543
It was set in Rapture, this city under the sea, in the same period.

26
00:02:55,043 --> 00:03:00,564
So it really made sense to use the score, or the style of the score, from the original

27
00:03:00,584 --> 00:03:01,064
Bioshock.

28
00:03:01,104 --> 00:03:08,086
But when we got to Bioshock Infinite, everyone, including myself, did not want to use the

29
00:03:08,126 --> 00:03:09,586
material from Bioshock 1 and 2.

30
00:03:09,646 --> 00:03:10,786
It just did not make sense.

31
00:03:10,846 --> 00:03:12,787
It was a completely unique game.

32
00:03:12,827 --> 00:03:13,627
There are parallels.

33
00:03:14,168 --> 00:03:15,429
And we'll talk a little bit about that

34
00:03:15,609 --> 00:03:16,869
during my presentation today.

35
00:03:17,109 --> 00:03:19,711
But really, we had a completely fresh game.

36
00:03:20,511 --> 00:03:21,992
It was set in a different period, 1912,

37
00:03:22,092 --> 00:03:26,494
in a city in the sky, almost sort of the polar opposite

38
00:03:26,534 --> 00:03:27,735
in a way, 180 degrees.

39
00:03:28,215 --> 00:03:30,416
And the bright, everything in Rapture

40
00:03:30,456 --> 00:03:32,717
was dark and dingy and drippy and wet.

41
00:03:32,737 --> 00:03:34,378
And everything in Bioshock Infinite

42
00:03:34,438 --> 00:03:38,020
is bright and sunny and blazing light.

43
00:03:38,120 --> 00:03:40,221
So it really was a different game.

44
00:03:41,182 --> 00:03:41,482
I had.

45
00:03:42,483 --> 00:03:46,066
I can't not mention the partners that I had in the game.

46
00:03:46,126 --> 00:03:48,728
First of all, the entire team at Irrational Games.

47
00:03:48,808 --> 00:03:50,470
Unfortunately, they did close their doors.

48
00:03:50,530 --> 00:03:52,672
But it's a great development team.

49
00:03:53,512 --> 00:03:58,976
Ken Levine, the creative director, is, I call him the Steve Jobs of video games.

50
00:03:59,156 --> 00:04:03,319
He really is a creative genius and I love working with him.

51
00:04:03,799 --> 00:04:08,122
Jim Bonney was the music director and Patrick Bothrop was the audio director

52
00:04:08,222 --> 00:04:12,445
and all those guys really did amazing things to make this game,

53
00:04:12,485 --> 00:04:14,046
this really, really wonderful game.

54
00:04:15,100 --> 00:04:18,804
And I am a contracted composer, so they were in Boston,

55
00:04:18,864 --> 00:04:21,847
and I was in LA basically throwing stuff over the fence

56
00:04:21,907 --> 00:04:23,449
and saying, how's this?

57
00:04:24,750 --> 00:04:27,733
When we first started, originally, I mean,

58
00:04:28,334 --> 00:04:30,396
because Bioshock 1 and 2 had been successful,

59
00:04:30,416 --> 00:04:33,139
there was no problem getting a budget

60
00:04:33,159 --> 00:04:34,621
for an orchestra, a large orchestra.

61
00:04:35,661 --> 00:04:39,824
But, and initially we thought, hey, this is going to be orchestral, you know.

62
00:04:39,864 --> 00:04:40,564
What do you want?

63
00:04:40,604 --> 00:04:41,444
Want to go to London?

64
00:04:42,125 --> 00:04:42,725
Where should we go?

65
00:04:42,745 --> 00:04:46,787
And it was like, okay, well, that's all cool and great.

66
00:04:46,827 --> 00:04:48,668
But it didn't turn out that way.

67
00:04:49,268 --> 00:04:51,089
A lot of things didn't turn out that way.

68
00:04:52,097 --> 00:04:55,120
And I think for good reason, and I'm grateful that they didn't.

69
00:04:56,081 --> 00:05:00,866
The first music, some of the first music I wrote for them was a...

70
00:05:01,487 --> 00:05:02,748
Well, I wrote a trailer.

71
00:05:03,409 --> 00:05:06,192
I wrote the score to a trailer, which was a big presentation trailer.

72
00:05:06,432 --> 00:05:07,373
And then they had like a...

73
00:05:10,433 --> 00:05:15,136
a press release conference, and it was a live, and they showed images from the game,

74
00:05:15,176 --> 00:05:19,238
and they wanted me to write some original music. So I'm going to play a little bit of that, just so that

75
00:05:19,979 --> 00:05:23,761
this was my initial early concept of what the score might sound like.

