78
00:07:02,827 --> 00:07:09,329
Which, because this is a dystopian world, and it's set in this city that's very American,

79
00:07:09,749 --> 00:07:16,571
and everything about it is patriotic, and yet what it is, it's a breakaway city,

80
00:07:16,631 --> 00:07:19,331
and it is really sort of a dystopian America.

81
00:07:19,451 --> 00:07:22,052
What would happen if everything went horribly wrong?

82
00:07:22,612 --> 00:07:24,233
So I thought that was appropriate.

83
00:07:25,831 --> 00:07:30,135
And then we, I messed around with a lot of different approaches.

84
00:07:30,616 --> 00:07:36,382
And it really wasn't until E3, there was an E3 the year before it came out, and they made a presentation there.

85
00:07:36,743 --> 00:07:40,707
And they had this AI character called Elizabeth, artificial intelligence.

86
00:07:40,867 --> 00:07:42,689
And she wasn't, she was...

87
00:07:43,950 --> 00:07:46,291
an important character, but not the central character.

88
00:07:46,651 --> 00:07:49,892
But the press, everything written about that E3

89
00:07:49,932 --> 00:07:52,132
presentation had Elizabeth, Elizabeth, Elizabeth.

90
00:07:52,192 --> 00:07:56,753
And it became really, really such an important part

91
00:07:56,793 --> 00:07:58,814
of what people were discussing on the game

92
00:07:58,854 --> 00:08:02,155
that it really had an influence on the whole creative team.

93
00:08:02,195 --> 00:08:05,115
And they decided to elevate her character to really

94
00:08:05,155 --> 00:08:06,235
your partner in the game.

95
00:08:06,275 --> 00:08:07,976
And so this artificial intelligence

96
00:08:08,316 --> 00:08:09,136
becomes your partner.

97
00:08:09,156 --> 00:08:11,237
And it was at that point that I realized

98
00:08:11,317 --> 00:08:13,737
that she was really important and that she

99
00:08:14,197 --> 00:08:16,018
I ought to write a theme for her.

100
00:08:16,498 --> 00:08:19,179
And so I wrote a theme, but I didn't want,

101
00:08:19,719 --> 00:08:22,080
knowing Ken Levine, Ken really responds

102
00:08:22,140 --> 00:08:23,240
to live performances.

103
00:08:23,320 --> 00:08:25,361
So I said to Jim, I said, you know,

104
00:08:25,381 --> 00:08:27,762
I don't really want to send this theme over to anyone.

105
00:08:27,862 --> 00:08:28,822
I want to record it live.

106
00:08:28,842 --> 00:08:30,022
And he goes, well, you know,

107
00:08:30,062 --> 00:08:31,363
we really don't have a budget for that,

108
00:08:31,423 --> 00:08:32,743
just to do mock-ups.

109
00:08:32,783 --> 00:08:34,644
And I go, well, I'm going to come out of pocket.

110
00:08:34,964 --> 00:08:36,064
I really want to record this.

111
00:08:36,344 --> 00:08:38,585
So I recorded it with one cello and one viola.

112
00:08:38,605 --> 00:08:39,485
We did some overdubs.

113
00:08:39,525 --> 00:08:39,745
And so.

114
00:08:40,566 --> 00:08:46,410
I did this really, really simple tonal triadic theme for her,

115
00:08:46,490 --> 00:08:53,395
but it was an important point in the realization for the approach for the entire score.

116
00:09:09,644 --> 00:09:09,804
You

117
00:09:44,744 --> 00:09:45,245
Thank you for watching.

118
00:10:09,500 --> 00:10:09,600
Ready?

119
00:10:09,620 --> 00:10:09,680
One.

120
00:10:09,700 --> 00:10:09,840
Get set.

121
00:10:09,860 --> 00:10:09,900
Go!

122
00:11:12,603 --> 00:11:18,809
So that simple theme, I sent that to Ken and Ken loved, I mean really loved it.

123
00:11:19,149 --> 00:11:24,815
It really moved him and it became my realization that I had that okay,

124
00:11:24,915 --> 00:11:29,399
this is the direction for the score. It's not orchestral, this is a really simple

125
00:11:29,459 --> 00:11:33,063
score and this involves really, really

126
00:11:34,524 --> 00:11:37,606
beautifully played, expressive solo instruments,

127
00:11:38,207 --> 00:11:44,511
and it somehow expressed the sadness of this world

128
00:11:45,031 --> 00:11:49,594
and expressed its, I don't know,

129
00:11:50,575 --> 00:11:52,876
I didn't, this is the thing, all throughout the game,

130
00:11:52,896 --> 00:11:54,397
they never told me how the game ended.

131
00:11:56,115 --> 00:11:59,638
I was scoring the end of the game and didn't understand what it was exactly.

132
00:11:59,978 --> 00:12:01,339
Because they were so secretive.

133
00:12:01,640 --> 00:12:03,842
But I knew there was this deep mystery.

134
00:12:03,882 --> 00:12:08,666
And so this simple music really was an epiphany for me and an epiphany for everyone in the

135
00:12:08,686 --> 00:12:08,906
game.

136
00:12:09,827 --> 00:12:11,428
So, the realization was...

137
00:12:12,828 --> 00:12:13,449
Keep it simple.

138
00:12:14,609 --> 00:12:16,629
Small string ensembles, not orchestral.

139
00:12:17,429 --> 00:12:20,710
And the positive response to live string players

140
00:12:21,010 --> 00:12:21,690
that Ken had.

141
00:12:22,411 --> 00:12:24,871
And then I did something that I've never done before.

142
00:12:25,031 --> 00:12:27,932
And it was really worked on this.

143
00:12:27,952 --> 00:12:29,832
I don't know if it would work for any other project.

144
00:12:30,032 --> 00:12:32,113
But what I did was I said to Jim, I said, look,

145
00:12:32,973 --> 00:12:33,753
we have all this money.

146
00:12:34,113 --> 00:12:34,893
We're not going to spend it.

147
00:12:35,494 --> 00:12:41,497
I think I have a way that's going to really work for me and for Ken and for you.

148
00:12:41,797 --> 00:12:43,938
I want to record my demos with live players.

149
00:12:45,039 --> 00:12:47,940
And he said, well, let's try that. He was open to that.

150
00:12:48,060 --> 00:12:52,263
So I did a couple of sessions with live players, and Ken was really digging the result.

151
00:12:52,563 --> 00:12:55,804
When I'd mock things up, he wasn't digging it or understanding it.

152
00:12:55,905 --> 00:12:58,226
When he heard it with live players, it was like...

153
00:12:58,606 --> 00:12:59,466
Yes, that's it.

154
00:12:59,606 --> 00:13:00,227
That sounds great.

155
00:13:00,507 --> 00:13:01,687
And it was just a realization.

156
00:13:01,827 --> 00:13:05,389
And I've never had more fun than working in that manner.

157
00:13:05,749 --> 00:13:06,650
It was just fantastic.

158
00:13:06,750 --> 00:13:07,450
I'd write the music.

159
00:13:08,070 --> 00:13:10,832
And then a week later, I'd bring a string quartet in,

160
00:13:11,132 --> 00:13:13,713
and we'd record for three hours.

161
00:13:14,553 --> 00:13:15,914
And two weeks later, I'd have.

162
00:13:16,054 --> 00:13:19,616
And eventually, it led me to the ideal string section

163
00:13:19,676 --> 00:13:20,456
for the game, which was.

164
00:13:21,337 --> 00:13:25,759
ten string players, three violins, three violas, three cellos, and one double bass.

165
00:13:25,839 --> 00:13:27,420
And that seemed to be sort of like ideal.

166
00:13:27,540 --> 00:13:31,143
Before that, I had as few as three sessions with string quartets,

167
00:13:31,383 --> 00:13:36,026
string quartet and double bass, just all sorts of different ensembles,

168
00:13:36,286 --> 00:13:38,747
and all of them with really great players.

169
00:13:38,767 --> 00:13:40,688
It was done in L.A., it was done at AFM,

170
00:13:41,069 --> 00:13:44,091
because it was grandfathered in from the old Bauschok game.

171
00:13:45,051 --> 00:13:47,613
And it was just totally working for him.

172
00:13:48,013 --> 00:13:49,995
And it was a really interesting way

173
00:13:50,075 --> 00:13:52,997
to really generate really cool music.

174
00:13:53,077 --> 00:13:57,181
And really, by the time I was nearly finished scoring it,

175
00:13:57,281 --> 00:13:59,483
most of the score had been recorded and was done.

176
00:13:59,503 --> 00:14:00,824
There was just an extra session or two

177
00:14:00,864 --> 00:14:02,785
that had to be put together.

178
00:14:03,963 --> 00:14:07,225
So there were several categories of this game

179
00:14:08,025 --> 00:14:09,086
the music would fit into.

180
00:14:09,146 --> 00:14:11,947
Now, there's also all the source music.

181
00:14:12,087 --> 00:14:13,788
I did not write the source music.

182
00:14:14,268 --> 00:14:17,390
Jim Bonney hired a bunch of really talented people

183
00:14:17,490 --> 00:14:20,592
to do this fantastic job on the source music,

184
00:14:20,732 --> 00:14:21,933
really, really brilliant stuff.

185
00:14:22,975 --> 00:14:25,016
a barbershop quartet singing Beach Boy songs.

186
00:14:25,036 --> 00:14:26,157
Just really cool stuff.

187
00:14:26,197 --> 00:14:28,258
And if you play the game and you understand

188
00:14:28,338 --> 00:14:31,339
how this game is sort of unstuck in time and anything

189
00:14:31,380 --> 00:14:34,601
is possible because time interacts with it

190
00:14:34,902 --> 00:14:37,483
in bizarre and crazy ways, they understand

191
00:14:37,563 --> 00:14:40,245
how a Beach Boy song could appear in 1912 being

192
00:14:40,285 --> 00:14:41,745
sung by a barbershop quartet.

193
00:14:43,146 --> 00:14:44,807
But the scripted events, scripted events

194
00:14:45,648 --> 00:14:48,509
are really essentially little vignettes,

195
00:14:48,549 --> 00:14:51,251
little movie vignettes that are locked to time.

196
00:14:51,291 --> 00:14:52,491
So you can score them like a picture.

197
00:14:53,669 --> 00:14:57,352
And really, the player has free agency, could walk away from them.

198
00:14:57,372 --> 00:14:59,234
And in fact, if you're playing the game for the fourth time,

199
00:14:59,254 --> 00:15:01,575
you're probably going to walk away from all the scripted events.

200
00:15:01,636 --> 00:15:05,118
But first time, you're definitely going to watch the scripted events,

201
00:15:05,178 --> 00:15:06,980
because something important is happening.

202
00:15:07,020 --> 00:15:09,161
And so most of these needed to be scored.

203
00:15:09,622 --> 00:15:11,223
So I'm going to play.

204
00:15:12,233 --> 00:15:16,119
This was a really interesting experiment initially.

205
00:15:16,419 --> 00:15:18,923
And really, once you get up to Columbia,

206
00:15:18,943 --> 00:15:21,486
the city in the sky, you end up in this little grotto.

207
00:15:21,527 --> 00:15:24,391
And then you open the door, and there is Columbia.

208
00:15:24,471 --> 00:15:25,392
And it's beautiful.

209
00:15:25,532 --> 00:15:26,754
It's really beautiful.

210
00:15:26,854 --> 00:15:27,275
It's like.

211
00:15:27,876 --> 00:15:30,739
It's not a dark place, at least at this point.

212
00:15:31,219 --> 00:15:35,744
I did not want the music to be scary at all.

213
00:15:35,944 --> 00:15:39,828
And yet, I didn't want the music just to be happy-go-lucky.

214
00:15:39,868 --> 00:15:41,670
So what I did was I combined...

215
00:15:42,130 --> 00:15:44,132
I listened to Stephen Foster songs.

216
00:15:44,733 --> 00:15:49,016
for a couple of days, Stephen Foster being the great American songwriter of the 19th century,

217
00:15:49,656 --> 00:15:54,559
and maybe there's a little New World Symphony. And I wrote this really simple, pretty melody

218
00:15:54,639 --> 00:16:00,663
with some simple chord changes, but then underneath it I added a chromatic, sort of slithery

219
00:16:02,184 --> 00:16:10,169
second layer that I thought represented what potentially is going to come at you in the city.

220
00:16:15,620 --> 00:16:17,240
thanks for watching, leading to this final video!

221
00:17:44,229 --> 00:17:48,252
So, and I used the video you see here as what I composed to.

222
00:17:48,593 --> 00:17:51,815
I just took that video and I thought it appropriate to bring that video.

223
00:17:52,155 --> 00:17:53,917
So, I just thought I'd show you this.

224
00:17:54,477 --> 00:17:59,901
I decided because I only had 10 players and because I wasn't sure how this was going to

225
00:17:59,961 --> 00:18:05,125
work when I recorded it, I thought I need to separate the tonal part from the chromatic

226
00:18:05,185 --> 00:18:05,386
part.

227
00:18:05,906 --> 00:18:06,086
So...

228
00:18:07,412 --> 00:18:09,793
Here just really is just a very simple,

229
00:18:09,853 --> 00:18:11,654
with just sustained chords.

